    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-20T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-20T02:00:00-05:00" n="391"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d391">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/991: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Josselyn</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-20T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 20, 1937—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 20—10:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Shanghai’s September 19, 8 p.m. and previous regarding trains to Canton. After
                    consulting by telephone with the Embassy at Nanking yesterday, I have warned
                    Americans that dangers of travel via Canton–Hankow Railway will probably
                    increase after September 24th.</p>
                <p>The efforts of the Tokyo Embassy to obtain from the Japanese promise to refrain
                    from attacking September 24th train from Hankow are appreciated but it should be
                    understood that few of the American population of this district have evacuated
                    and that the intimation from the Japanese authorities that they will feel free
                    after midnight of September 24th to take action against the railway, not
                    excluding attacks on passenger trains, will serve as a formidable deterrent to
                    further evacuation.</p>
                <p>Sent to the Department and Nanking, repeated to Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Josselyn</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
